{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586629","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586629"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:36:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:36:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15082"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15082"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.68,0.2,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7770"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69293"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7770"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15082"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54746"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3005"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8129"},{"type":"tags","id":"8572"},{"type":"tags","id":"11073"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18961"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18963"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23127"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69293"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBladder cancer staging is based on the depth of tumour invasion through the bladder wall, while grading reflects the degree of cellular differentiation. Treatment approaches vary depending on both these factors.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following bladder cancer classifications typically requires radical cystectomy with urinary diversion plus radiotherapy and/or chemotherapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Low stage, high grade superficial tumour","High stage, high grade muscle-invasive tumour","High stage, low grade muscle-invasive tumour","Low stage, low grade superficial tumour","Widely metastatic disease"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh stage, high grade muscle-invasive tumour\u003C/strong\u003E requires aggressive multimodal treatment including radical cystectomy with urinary diversion, often combined with chemotherapy and/or radiotherapy to optimise survival outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other classifications generally require different approaches:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow stage, high grade superficial tumours\u003C/strong\u003E are typically managed with transurethral resection and intravesical therapy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh stage, low grade muscle-invasive tumours\u003C/strong\u003E are rare, as higher stage tumours are usually high grade\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow stage, low grade superficial tumours\u003C/strong\u003E can usually be managed with transurethral resection alone\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWidely metastatic disease\u003C/strong\u003E is generally treated with systemic chemotherapy or targeted palliative radiotherapy, with surgery reserved for palliation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of high stage (muscle invasion) and high grade (poor differentiation) represents aggressive disease requiring multimodal therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Muscle-invasive (high stage) bladder cancer with high grade histology requires aggressive multimodal treatment including surgery and adjuvant therapy.","Treatment decisions for bladder cancer are based on both stage (depth of invasion) and grade (cellular differentiation).","Cystectomy with urinary diversion is the standard surgical approach for muscle-invasive bladder cancer."],"references":["Comp\u00e9rat E, Amin MB, Cathomas R, Choudhury A, De Santis M, Kamat A, Stenzl A, Thoeny HC, Witjes JA. Current best practice for bladder cancer: a narrative review of diagnostics and treatments. Lancet. 2022 Nov 12;400(10364):1712-1721. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(22)01188-6. Epub 2022 Sep 26. PMID: 36174585","Lenis AT, Lec PM, Chamie K, Mshs MD. Bladder Cancer: A Review. JAMA. 2020 Nov 17;324(19):1980-1991. doi: 10.1001/jama.2020.17598. PMID: 33201207","Leslie SW, Soon-Sutton TL, Aeddula NR. Bladder Cancer. 2024 Aug 15. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725608","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54746"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15082"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54746"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T18:22:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T18:24:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7770"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69293"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024